\section*{1. Motivation: Joint Random Variables}

\begin{itemize}
    \item In many situations, we consider \textbf{two (or more) random variables simultaneously}.
    
    \item Examples:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Height and weight
        \item IQ and birthweight
        \item Exercise frequency and heart disease
        \item Air pollution and illness rate
        \item Number of friends and age
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item Joint distributions allow:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Computation of probabilities involving multiple variables
        \item Understanding relationships between variables
    \end{itemize}
    
    \item If variables are not independent:
    \begin{itemize}
        \item Dependence is analyzed using \textbf{covariance and correlation}
    \end{itemize}
\end{itemize}

